A sampling of street trees was performed during 2022 using random belt transects of 0.10 ha size in Delhi (18 transects) and Ranchi (20 transects) cities, where the girth at breast height (GBH i.e., 1.37 m above the ground) and the height of each adult tree (≥10 cm GBH) were measured using measuring tape and a rangefinder, respectively. Tree saplings and seedlings were sampled in 3 random quadrats of 5 m × 5 m and 1 m × 1 m size, respectively. Species were identified up to species level following regional flora, published literature, consulting botanical survey of India and field taxonomists. The population structure and vertical stratification were analyzed by grouping all of the individual trees following Saikia et al. [46] (Table 1.1
                        ). The regeneration status of trees was evaluated by quantifying the overall population density of seedlings, saplings, and adults by following Shankar [47] (Table 1.2

                        ). On the other hand, the quantitative analyses of vegetation were performed following ecological indices as summarized in Table 1.3
                        .

The species dispersion pattern was determined by using abundance to abundance-to-frequency ratio [56], which implies regular distribution if A/F < 0.025, random if A/F = 0.025–0.05, and contagious propagation if A/F > 0.05 [57]. Raunkiaer's law of frequency [58] was implemented to put the tree species into one of five groups for their frequency distribution (Table 1.4
                        ), while the species were categorized into different rarity classes following Pragasan and Parthasarathy [59] (
                        Table 1.5

                        ).

A total of 96 species of trees of 86 genera belonging to 34 families were documented in the urban streets of Ranchi, while in Delhi, a total of 64 species were reported belonging to 56 genera and 28 families (Figs. 2 and 3)
                        . While the earlier studies reported comparatively less plant species richness in Chengdu city, China (57 spp. of 28 families) [22], Bhubaneswar (44 spp. of 22 families) [60], and the urban-rural area of Jaunpur (54 spp. of 23 families) [61] in India, but higher species richness in Zomba City of Malawi (168 spp. of 47 families) [62], the northern part of mega-city Bengaluru (93 spp. of 39 families) [63], and Pasighat (103 spp. of 45 families) [64] in India (Table 2
                        ). Comparatively higher species richness in Ranchi City as compared to Delhi metropolis may be due to the differences in management approaches, planting history, development patterns, edaphic factors, and spatial variation in floral composition [65]. The high species richness in a region signifies healthier ecosystems than the regions with poor species richness [66,67]. Similarly, among Nordic cities, Malmo has the highest urban tree diversity (113) flourishing, after Turku (74) and Copenhagen (66) [68]. On the other hand, Fabaceae was the predominant family in both the cities, and in Ranchi, it has 16 different species (17%) followed by Moraceae with 13 species (12%), and Rubiaceae with 6 species (6%), while in Delhi it has 18 (28%) different species followed by Moraceae with 7 (9%) and Myrtaceae with 4 (6%) species. Fabaceae was also found to be a predominant family in other parts of Indian cities like Bilaspur [69], Coimbatore [70], and Puducherry [71] due to ecological adaptivity, selective utilization, and conservation by government and private ownership [72]. Out of the total 96 species in Ranchi, 70% (59 spp.) were IUCN Red-listed of which 88% (60 spp.) were Least Concerned (LC), 4% (03 spp.) Near Threatened (NT) (Aegle marmelos (L.) Corrêa, Dypsis lutescens (H.Wendl.) Beentje & J.Dransf, and Eucalyptus camaldulensis Dehnh.), 3% (02 spp.) Vulnerable (VU) (Jacaranda mimosifolia D. Don and Litchi chinensis Sonn.), and 1% (01 sp.) Endangered (EN) (Tectona grandis L.), while 3% (02 spp.) Data Deficient (DD) (Carica papaya L. and Mangifera indica L.). On the other hand, in Delhi, out of 64 plant species, around 74% of species were IUCN Red-listed, of which 86.6% (39 spp.) LC, 2.2% (1 sp. each) NT (A. marmelos), VU (J. mimosifolia), and EN (T. grandis) and 6.6% (3 spp.) DD. A higher proportion of IUCN Red-Listed tree species has significant consequences for human accessibility, conservation, management policy suggestions, and future protection and isolation improvements. In general, a higher percentage denotes a greater concern for the conservation of biodiversity, while a decreasing trend of IUCN red-listed tree species suggests a negative influence of people on biodiversity. The presence of IUCN red-listed tree species is vital for managers, conservationists, and city planners since they are crucial for the protection and management of biodiversity in urban areas [73]. On the other hand, the percentage of native species in Ranchi and Delhi is 64% (62 spp.) and 69% (44 spp.), respectively, while the percentage of introduced species is 36% (35 spp.) and 31% (20 spp.), respectively. There are more introduced species in cities than in rural regions because of factors including government and private ownership favouring non-native trees for ornamental, shelterbelt, and development of UGSs [74]. Similar trends of indigenous and introduced species were also reported in Karwar, Karnataka, India [75]. The higher percentage of introduced species signifies the transformation of homogenous habitat towards heterogeneity [76] that hinders species composition, local climate filtration, and monitoring of all species within that community [65]. The majority of the street trees were contagiously distributed in both Ranchi (97.29%) and Delhi (100.00%), while only 2.71% species (Araucaria columnaris (J. R. Forst.) Hook, Monoon longifolium (Sonn.) B.Xue & R.M.K.Saunders, and Morus alba L.) were randomly distributed tree species in Ranchi. The distribution of species is contagious in naturally occurring vegetation, but random in highly homogeneous ecosystems [77]. This is because contagious distribution is heavily influenced by factors such as seed dispersal, mode of reproduction, local habitat, and the daily and periodic weather in a given area [78].

The height distribution of street trees was documented to understand their established age, unique ecological significance like distribution of light and potential to receive precipitation in different strata [80]. The height of trees ranged from 2 to 22 m with a mean height of 10 m ± 0.08 (SE) in Ranchi, while it ranged from 1.5 to 16.5 m with a mean height of 6 m ± 0.06 (SE) in Delhi. The majority of individuals (44.39%) on the streets of Ranchi were recorded in the height class of 10–20 m (canopy strata), while in Delhi majority of individuals (50.95%) were recorded in the height class of 5–10 m (understorey strata) (
                        Fig. 7
                        ). The emergent strata (>20 m height) at Ranchi were occupied by the 08 individuals of only two species (E. camaldulensis and Delonix regia (Bojer ex Hook.) Raf.), while the canopy layer was dominated by the individuals (1236) of the majority of tree species (70 spp.) including M. indica and Acacia auriculiformis A.Cunn. ex Benth. On the other hand, the street trees of Delhi were comparatively young without any individuals in the emergent layer and only a few individuals (67) in the canopy layer of 24 different plant species including Neltuma juliflora (Sw.) Raf., while the majority of the individuals (1079) in the understorey layer in Delhi was dominated by 57 different plant species including N. juliflora, Pongamia pinnata (L.) Pierre, and Putranjiva roxburghii Wall. Tree composition at different strata helps to understand the changes in understorey plant communities such as response to light, regeneration, growth, species coexistence, and habitat [81].

Besides, this study illustrates clear differences in street tree density (the number of trees per hectare of street) between the two cities. At the same time, Delhi has greater tree density (673 ind. ha−1) compared to Ranchi city (217 ind. ha−1). Alternatively, the density of street trees in different streets of Ranchi ranges from 62 to 612 ind. ha−1 with a mean of 217 ind. ha−1 ± 31 (SE), while in Delhi it ranged from 260 to 1890 ind. ha−1, with a mean of 630 ind. ha−1 ± 87 (SE) (
                        Fig. 8
                        ). In the streets of Ranchi, M. indica contributed the highest density (29 ind. ha−1), followed by A. auriculiformis (16 ind. ha−1), and S. robusta (14 ind. ha−1), while in Delhi, N. juliflora (109 ind. ha−1) contributed the highest followed by P. pinnata (83 ind. ha−1), P. roxburghi (63 ind. ha−1), and C. fistula (57 ind. ha−1) (
                        Table 3

                        ). Although the density of street trees in Ranchi is quite less compared to Delhi, it has comparatively higher street tree density than in Minas Gerais, Brazil (167 ind. ha−1) [82] and Chennai, India (104 ind. ha−1) [83]. The density of street trees in Delhi is comparable to the tree density in the tropical dry deciduous forest of Central India (520 ind. ha−1) [84] and protected forests of Gulmarg Wildlife Sanctuary, Jammu and Kashmir (185–810 ind. ha−1) [85]. The density of tree species varies among cities due to different urban land uses [86,87], desired benefits of trees, initiatives, management approaches, afforestation, and urban planning [88]. The variations in the density of street trees in both the studied cities as the urban planning and afforestation approach in Ranchi are limited to selective species for desired benefits of trees (i.e., ornamentation and shelterbelt) and some vegetation also faces anthropogenic pressure such as lopping, grazing, fuelwood collection, and unauthorized clearance of vegetation for urban sprawl, while in Delhi the allotment and displacement of vegetated areas have been influenced by city development patterns. Although there are more green areas near the city centre, there are differences in the number of parks and gardens throughout Delhi city [89]. Although there are significant differences in the tree density in both the cities, the total basal cover of street trees in Ranchi (20.67 m2ha−1) and Delhi (21.70 m2ha−1) were comparable due to the predominance of young and adult individuals (GBH ≥30–90 cm) in Ranchi, while in Delhi it is dominated by pole and young individuals (GBH ≥10–60 cm). However, it is quite less compared to urban forest patches of Puducherry (34.27 m2ha−1) [71] and Bengaluru (46.67 m2ha−1) [63]. The variations in basal cover at different sites are mainly due to differences in species composition, successional strategies, age of individuals, physicochemical properties of soil, climate, biogeography, and degree of disturbances [90]. The major contributors of basal cover at Ranchi were M. indica (2.86 m2 ha−1), E. camaldulensis (2.38 m2 ha−1), and S. robusta (2.11 m2 ha−1), while N. juliflora (4.92 m2 ha−1), P. pinnata (3.08 m2 ha−1), and S.cumini (1.29 m2 ha−1) were the major contributors at Delhi. Significant contrasts in species richness, diversity, density, and basal cover of street trees between Ranchi and Delhi clearly show that local legacy movements, socio-demographic aspirations, and environmental contexts affect the future trajectory of urban forests [91]. Based on the research findings, it can be recommended that native tree species like S. robusta (17.12), Bridelia retusa (L.) A. Juss. (12.26), Ficus benghalensis L.rtr (9.41), Syzygium cumini (L.) Skeels (9.32), and Artocarpus heterophyllus Lam. (8.63) with the highest IVI values (>8.00) may be planted along streets of Ranchi city for development of UGSs, while along the streets of Delhi, P. pinnata (34.29), Cassia fistula L. (20.17), P. roxburghi (18.03), S. cumini (10.26), and Holoptelea integrifolia (Roxb.) (5.01) may be planted as they have the highest IVI values (>5.00).

The present study showed maximum species richness in frequency class A˃B > C > D > E in both cities according to Raunkiaer's frequency distribution (
                        Fig. 4

                        ) signifying that the plant community at both the cities were heterogeneous. Most of the street trees at Ranchi (80%) and Delhi (49%) had shown low frequency belonging to Raunkiaer's frequency class A, followed by B (16% and (9%), C (12% and 2%), D (2% and 1%), and E (1% and 0%). On the other hand, the percentage of species in various rarity classes at Ranchi had shown a high percentage of very rare species (36.9%), followed by rare species (35.1%), common species (25.2%), and dominant species (1.8%). Whereas, the highest percentage of rare species (54.4%) were documented at Delhi, followed by very rare species (24.6%), common species (14%), and dominant species (7%) (Fig. 5
                        ). Some of the very rare species documented in Ranchi were Adenanthera pavonina L., Albizia chinensis (Osbeck) Merr., and Breynia vitis-idaea (Burm.f.) C.E.C.Fisch., while Ailanthus excelsa Roxb., Casuarina equisetifolia L., and Cryptostegia grandiflora Roxb. ex R.Br. were some of the very rare species documented in Delhi. The rare species have keystone and functional roles to contribute towards ecosystem recovery and community stability [92], therefore the presence of rare species in both the studied cities is likely to reduce perturbations on common species and increase resilience potential to recover any ecological disturbances.

Beta (β) diversity of street trees of Ranchi and Delhi was determined by the Sorensen similarity index (SI), Jaccard similarity index (Cj), and Bray Curtis dissimilarity index as given in Table 1.3. The similarity of street trees of Ranchi and Delhi is quite low in terms of all the β-diversity indices (SI = 38.75% and dissimilarity = 61.25%; Cj = 0.24 and dissimilarity = 0.76; BCij = 0.61 and similarity = 0.39) (
                        Table 5

                        ). The high variations in the street tree composition in both cities were mainly due to the changes in climatic and edaphic factors, colonial history, pre-existing vegetation, ecological disturbances, cultural drivers, city tiers, governance, and monetary budgets [99].

The study of the overall status of seedling, sapling, and adult trees in a region is used to determine the regeneration potential of existing tree species which gives an idea about the future composition of forest communities [106]. Out of the total tree species in Ranchi (96) and Delhi (64), the maximum species have shown no regeneration in Ranchi (62.5%) and Delhi (57.38%), followed by fair regeneration in Ranchi (19.79%) and Delhi (22.95%), good regeneration in Ranchi (17.71%) and Delhi (11.48%), while absence of poor and new regeneration in Ranchi (0.00%). On the other hand, 8.20% of species have shown poor regeneration and 1.64% are new (Balanites roxburghii Planch.) in the street tree communities of Delhi (
                        Fig. 6

                        ). Among both studied cities, the overall regeneration status is quite concerning as the majority of the street trees had been found only in the adult stage without any seedlings and saplings (no regeneration) (Table 6
                        ). The species with poor and no regeneration status may disappear from the particular city soon as a result of poor management of urban trees, human interference, and other biotic and edaphic factors [107]. It is recommended that re-greening and creating diverse tracts of native trees in urban niches should be increased for positive aspects and protections against environmental degradation [108].
